{
  "doc_id": "31265",
  "text": "As to G6PC3, its deficiency is implicated in the severe congenital neutropenia syndrome type 4 (SCN4) that is not a real glycogen storage disease but can be considered a glycogen storage disease 1 related syndrome (GSD1rs). G6PC3 deficit shares neutropenia and neutrophil function defects typical to GSD1b [CITATION_1] . G6PC3 is relevant to maintain macrophage/neutrophil homeostasis, though the exact mechanism has been elusive for a long period. It has been proposed that a dysfunctional G6PC3/G6PT complex may be related to the problem. G6PC3-similar to G6PC1-needs G6P supply in the ER lumen; thus, if the complex doesn't work properly, the hydrolysis cannot work either. It has been evidenced that in GSD1b patients, neutrophils are more prone to apoptosis [CITATION_2] . Neutrophils need glucose, and the destruction of G6PC3/G6PT complex alters glucose recycling in the ER. Thus, disturbed glucose homeostasis leads to neutropenia and neutrophil dysfunction. Nonetheless, also monocyte/macrophages are affected [CITATION_3] . It is also possible that Hypoxia Inducible Factor HIF-1alpha is involved in the process [CITATION_4] . Eventually, defective glucose production in the ER can be the cause of aberrant glycosylation [CITATION_5] , leading to neutrophil functional derangement. However, a very recent study [CITATION_6] indicated that this enzyme could efficiently hydrolyze and eliminate the non-classical toxic metabolite 1,5-anhydroglucitol, at least, in human leukocytes. These findings provided a logical explanation for the leukocyte pathology of patients with G6PC3 and G6PT mutations and supported the hypothesis that G6PC3 would behave as a metabolite repair enzyme acting on substrates other than G6P [CITATION_7] .",
